<h2>What Internet Explorer 6 and lower are Missing</h2>
<p>The following features are used on this site and supported by all the above browser but not Internet Explorer.</p>
<ul>
 <li>Proper Layout:  This site has been kludged to work with Internet Explorer where necessary to provide basic functionality.
 Accordingly, there are many aspects of this site that are rendered slightly incorrectly by Internet Explorer.
 Absolutely no browser specific kludges where necessary to get this site to render properly with all of the above browsers.</li>
 <li>Translucent PNG's: Many of the images (not product images) use PNG transparency to smoothly blend with the background.  (Fixed in Internet Explorer 7 Beta)</li>
 <li>Ancestor hover selector:  The items in product categories list will show sub categories when the cursor is positioned over them.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What Internet Explorer 7 is Missing</h2>
<p>A majority of the major problems have been addressed in Internet Explorer 7.  But it still has the following problems.</p>
<ul>
 <li>Proper table layout override allowing table layout without table based markup.  Properly adapting content to alternative media like print is made more difficult without this.</li>
 <li>A z-index bug causing improper display of dropdown menues with table layout.  
 <li>SVG support.</li>
</ul>
 
<h2>Why Web Standards are Important</h2>

<p>The internet is a communication tool and like all forms of communication it requires convention.
Much like the meaning of the words we use, every aspect of the internet requires conventions allowing different software and devices to properly interpret the communications.
The <%= link_to "W3C", "http://www.w3c.org/" %> has established recommendations for the interpretation of HTML, the core language of a web browser.
Ideally a web site written to these standards can be viewed properly by any browser and today this is essentially true with the exception of Internet Explorer.
Internet Explorer follows its own conventions similar but not completely consistent with established HTML recommendation unlike all all its competitors.
Accordingly, developers must spend time working around problems in Internet Explorer, taking away from time improving the site.</p>

<p>Most web pages are written in a way that intermingles semantic information with presentation information.
W3C recommendations strive to provide a clean separation between the meaning of a web page and the specifics of how it is presented.
In doing so, the presentation of a web site can be more easily adapted to different formats like a computer screen, a cell phone, or for the blind.
In addition, this separation can drastically reduce the size of a web site.
In fact, the pages on this site are less than 1/10th the size of some of <a href="http://www.4imprint.com/">our</a> <a href="http://www.branders.com/">competitors</a> without a substantial difference in useful content per page, resulting in faster browsing for you and lower hosting costs for us.
</p>

<h3>Why not just write for Internet Explorer?</h3>
<p>Internet Explorer does not support compelling features like Scalable Vector Graphics, most of the CSS 3 specification and many aspects of CSS 2.1.
In other words, one can not build as sophisticated a site if you are constrained to support Internet Explorer vs. ALL of the browsers listed above.
W3C web recommendations are available today for features that will take years for any of these browsers to fully implement, but all of them are ahead of Internet Explorer.
If the past is an indicator, without strong completive pressure (like from Netscape years ago) Microsoft will not improve Internet Explorer.</p>
